attacks.name: Wrap
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, the Defending Pokémon is now Paralyzed.

attacks.name: Deadly Poison
attacks.text: The Defending Pokémon is now Poisoned. If the Defending Pokémon was already Poisoned, this attack does 10 more damage.

attacks.name: Strength in Numbers
attacks.text: Does 10 more damage for each of your Benched Nidoran?, Nidoran?, Nidorino, Nidorina, Nidoking, and Nidoqueen.

attacks.name: Fury Swipes
attacks.text: Flip 3 coins. This attack does 30 damage times the number of heads.

attacks.name: Swift Lunge
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If tails, this attack does nothing and this Pokémon does 20 damage to itself.

attacks.name: Disable
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, choose 1 of the Defending Pokémon's attacks. That Pokémon can't use that attack during your opponent's next turn.

attacks.name: Psybeam
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, the Defending Pokémon is now Confused.

attacks.name: Sway
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon during your opponent's next turn.

attacks.name: Stun Spore
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, the Defending Pokémon is now Paralyzed.

attacks.name: Regeneration
attacks.text: Remove all damage counters from this Pokémon. Discard all Evolution cards and Energy cards attached to this Pokémon.

attacks.name: Dissolve
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, discard 1 Energy card attached to the Defending Pokémon.

effect.name: Poison Mist
effect.text: Once during your turn (before your attack), you may flip a coin. If heads, until the end of your next turn, all Poisoned Pokémon take 20 damage instead of 10 damage from Poison after each player's turn. This power can't be used and stops working while this Pokémon is Asleep, Confused, or Paralyzed.

attacks.name: Gas Explosion
attacks.text: This Pokémon does 30 damage to itself. If this attack Knocks Out the Defending Pokémon and your opponent chooses a new Active Pokémon, your opponent's new Active Pokémon becomes Poisoned.

attacks.name: Slashing Strike
attacks.text: Scyther can't use this attack during your next turn. (Benching or evolving Scyther ends this effect.)

attacks.name: Foxfire
attacks.text: Before doing damage, you may switch the Defending Pokémon with 1 of your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

attacks.name: Errand-Running
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, search your deck for a Trainer card, reveal it, and put it into your hand. Shuffle your deck afterwards.

attacks.name: Ember
attacks.text: Discard 1 Fire Energy card attached to this Pokémon in order to use this attack.

attacks.name: Live Coal
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If tails, discard 1 Energy card attached to this Pokémon.

attacks.name: Burning Fire
attacks.text: When you use this attack, you may discard any number of Fire Energy cards attached to your Pokémon in play. This attack does 10 damage plus 10 more damage for each Fire Energy card you discarded in this way.

attacks.name: Psychic
attacks.text: Does 10 more damage for each Energy attached to the Defending Pokémon.

attacks.name: Salt Water
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, search your deck for up to 3 Water Energy cards and attach them to this Pokémon.

attacks.name: Double-Edged Claw
attacks.text: During your opponent's next turn, all damage done to this Pokémon is doubled.

attacks.name: Hide
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, prevent all effects of attacks, including damage, done to this Pokémon during your opponent's next turn.

attacks.name: Water Gun
attacks.text: Does 10 more damage for each Water Energy attached to this Pokémon but not used to pay for this attack's Energy cost. You can't add more than 20 damage in this way.

attacks.name: Water Bomb
attacks.text: Does 10 damage for each Water Energy attached to this Pokémon but not used to pay for this attack's Energy cost to your opponent's Benched Pokémon in any way you like. You can't do more than 20 damage in this way. (Don't apply Weakness or Resistance for Benched Pokémon.)

attacks.name: Strange Beam
attacks.text: During your opponent's next turn, your Water Pokémon that have damage counters on them have no Weakness.

effect.name: Fossil Guidance
effect.text: Once during your turn (before your attack), you may flip a coin. If heads, put 1 Mysterious Fossil from your discard pile into your hand. This power can't be used if Omanyte is Asleep, Confused, or Paralyzed.

attacks.name: Psycho Panic
attacks.text: If the Defending Pokémon is Psychic, this attack's base damage is doubled.

attacks.name: Blink
attacks.text: If an attack damages this Pokémon during your opponent's next turn, flip a coin. If heads, prevent that damage. (Any other effects of attacks still happen.)

attacks.name: Energy Restore
attacks.text: Put a Special Energy card from your discard pile into your hand.

attacks.name: Energy Shock
attacks.text: If your opponent attaches an Energy card to the Defending Pokémon during his or her next turn, that Pokémon becomes Paralyzed.

attacks.name: Big Yawn
attacks.text: Both the Defending Pokémon and this Pokémon are now Asleep.

attacks.name: Big Snore
attacks.text: You can only use this attack if this Pokémon is Asleep.

attacks.name: Spookify
attacks.text: Your opponent can't play Trainer cards from his or her hand during his or her next turn.

attacks.name: Darkness
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, the Defending Pokémon is now Confused.

attacks.name: Eerie Light
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, the Defending Pokémon is now Confused.

attacks.name: Grudge
attacks.text: Does 20 damage plus 10 more damage for each Prize card your opponent has taken.

attacks.name: Poltergeist
attacks.text: Look at your opponent's hand. This attack does 10 damage times the number of Trainer cards your opponent has in his or her hand.

attacks.name: Bad Dreams
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, the Defending Pokémon is now Asleep. If tails, the Defending Pokémon is now Confused.

effect.name: Puppet Master
effect.text: If a Clefairy Doll is your Active Pokémon, it may use any of this Pokémon's attacks as long as this Pokémon has enough Energy cards attached to it to pay for that attack's Energy cost. (The Clefairy Doll can make that attack even if it does not have the appropriate number or type of Energy attached to it necessary to make the attack.)

attacks.name: Mind Shock
attacks.text: This attack's damage isn't affected by Weakness or Resistance.

attacks.name: Complete Recovery
attacks.text: Discard all Energy cards attached to this Pokémon. Then, remove all damage counters and markers from this Pokémon and this Pokémon is no longer Poisoned or Confused.

attacks.name: Psycho Blast
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, discard 1 Energy card attached to the Defending Pokémon.

attacks.name: Sand Veil
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, prevent all damage done to this Pokémon during your opponent's next turn.

attacks.name: Rolling Needle
attacks.text: Flip 3 coins. This attack does 10 more damage for each heads. Then, this Pokémon does 10 damage times the number of heads to itself.

attacks.name: Wicked Jab
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, the Defending Pokémon is now Paralyzed.

attacks.name: Focus Blast
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 20 damage to 1 of your opponent's Pokémon. Apply Weakness and Resistance.

attacks.name: Boulder Smash
attacks.text: Flip 2 coins. For each heads, put 1 damage counter on 1 your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

attacks.name: Bone Toss
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 30 damage to the Defending Pokémon. If tails, this attack does 10 damage to 1 of your opponent's Benched Pokémon. (Don't apply Weakness and Resistance for Benched Pokémon.)

attacks.name: Mountain Break
attacks.text: Discard the top 5 cards of your deck. If any of those cards are Fighting Energy cards, put them into your hand.

attacks.name: One-Two Strike
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 20 more damage.

attacks.name: Twister
attacks.text: Unless this attack Knocks Out the Defending Pokémon, flip a coin. If heads, return all Trainer cards and Energy cards attached to the Defending Pokémon to your opponent's hand.

attacks.name: Fly
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If tails, this attack does nothing. If heads, prevent all effects of attacks, including damage, done to this Pokémon during your opponent's next turn.

attacks.name: Tail Drop
attacks.text: Flip 2 coins. If either of them is tails, this attack does nothing.

attacks.name: Kicking and Stamping
attacks.text: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 10 more damage. If tails, your opponent switches the Defending Pokémon with 1 of his or her Benched Pokémon.

data.name: Pokémon Retransfer
rules: Put an Evolution card from your discard pile on top of your deck.

data.name: Pokémon Tower
rules: This card stays in play when you play it. Discard this card if another Stadium card comes into play.
"If the effect of a Pokémon Power, attack, Energy card or Trainer card would put a card in a discard pile into its owners hand, that card stays in that discard pile instead."

data.name: 4 Prize Battle
rules: These rules have been used in official tournaments. Try playing when you are short on time, such as during break time at school, etc.!

"This is a rule by which each player puts out 4 Prize cards to battle when he or she would put out 6 Prize cards to battle. The player who Knocks Out 4 of his or her opponents Pokémon and draws all 4 Prize cards wins.\n\nThese rules have been used in official tournaments. Try playing when you are short on time, such as during break time at school, etc."

data.name: 20 Damage from Confusion
rules: Pokémon card rules recommended for beginners. Official tournaments have since adopted this rule.

This is a simple rule for when a Pokémon uses an attack while it is Confused and the coin flip was tails (when the Pokémon was Confused). Regardless of the type of attack, the Pokémon that used the attack itself receives 20 damage.\n\nPokémon card rules recommended for beginners. Official tournaments have since adopted this rule.

data.name: 3 Deck Battle
rules: If you have a lot of decks, try it when you have plenty of time to play!

Each battling player readies 3 decks with different contents. Next, they put their decks face down in play and decide the order of the decks with which they will battle. Also, they start battling with the decks 1 time each in the decided order. The player who won twice in the end wins.\n\nIf you have a lot of decks, try it when you have plenty of time to play!

data.name: 3 vs 3 Dugtrio Team Battle
rules: If you have more friends playing with Pokémon cards, give it a try!

"Three people form a team, each bringing decks with different contents, and battle team vs. team. Each team decides the order its members will battle in, and the battles begin, 1 on 1. When all 3 persons battles are over, the team that won twice wins.\n\nIf you have more friends playing with Pokémon cards, give it a try!"

data.name: Deck Exchange
rules: If your deck is too strong you may lose after the exchange, so make a point of the deck you construct!

"Each player brings a deck and battles 3 times. They battle the first time with their deck, the second time they exchange decks, and the third time with their decks once more. A player gets 1 point each time he or she won with his or her deck and 2 points when he or she won with his or her opponents deck. With the results of the 3 battles, the player with the higher total number of points wins.\n\nIf your deck is too strong you may lose after the exchange, so make a point of the deck you construct!"

data.name: Imakuni?'s Corner
rules: Hello! How is everyone doing? I started Pokémon cards recently!! Pokémon cards are extremely interesting, but there is one thing I sometimes want to say!! Da-dum That is, to say The "Imakuni? card" is useless!! Da-da-dum Does everyone know what the Imakuni? card does? It says "When you play this card, your Active Pokémon is now Confused."!? It\s your Pokémon, y-o-u-r-s! How can that be?! So, Imakuni? fans all across the country are crying. They\re crying. But the Imakuni? card\s in my deck. I\ll use it someday!
